  "local_port": 54150,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I have a flight to prague. But In between I have to change flight at Paris! How to do that?",
  "response": "Changing flights in Paris typically involves a few steps, but the process can vary depending on the airline and whether your flights are booked on the same ticket or separate tickets. Here\u2019s a general guide to help you navigate your connection smoothly:\n\n1. **Check Your Itinerary**: Review your flight confirmation to see if your flights are on the same airline or if they are part of a code-share. If they're on the same ticket, your bags may be checked through to Prague.\n\n2. **Arrival at Paris Airport**: Most international flights to Paris land at Charles de Gaulle Airport (CDG). Make sure to check which terminal your incoming flight arrives at and where your connecting flight departs from.\n\n3. **Follow the Signs**: Upon landing, follow the signs for \"Connections\" or \"Transits.\" The airport will have clear signage to guide you to the transfer area.\n\n4. **Security/Passport Control**: If you are arriving from outside the Schengen Area, you may need to go through passport control. If you have to switch terminals, you may have to go through security again as well.\n\n5. **Checking in for Your Next Flight**: If your flights are on the same ticket, you may not need to check in again. If they are on different tickets, make sure to check in for your next flight at the airline\u2019s desk or kiosk.\n\n6. **Baggage**: If your bags are checked through to Prague, you won\u2019t have to claim them in Paris. If you have separate tickets, you\u2019ll need to collect your bags and check them in again for your flight to Prague.\n\n7. **Time to Connect**: Make sure you have a sufficient layover to accommodate any delays or the time it takes to go through security and passport control. A minimum of 1.5 to 2 hours is generally recommended.\n\n8. **Departure Gate**: Check the departure screen for your flight to Prague to find the terminal and gate information. Allow enough time to reach your gate.\n\n9. **Language**: English is commonly spoken at CDG, but having a translation app or phrasebook can help in case you need assistance.\n\n10. **Ask for Help**: Don\u2019t hesitate to ask airport staff for directions or assistance if needed.\n\nMake sure to keep an eye on flight updates, as gates can change. Safe travels!",
